        [![Open in Colab](https://colab.research.google.com/assets/colab-badge.svg)](https://colab.research.google.com/github/habib-hajjioui/Hotel-Revenue-Quality-Cancellation-Analysis/blob/main/Hotel_Revenue_Quality_%26_Cancellation_Intelligence.ipynb) ,
        "# Hotel Revenue Quality & Cancellation Intelligence\n",
        "## A Business Intelligence Portfolio Project\n",
        "### City Hotel Booking Analysis — 2015 to 2017\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "> **Analyst Note:** This project was built as a portfolio demonstration of applied business intelligence in the hospitality industry. Every number in this notebook has been verified through Python code. Every business interpretation is grounded in verified data. Claims that rely on assumptions are labeled as such.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# 1. Project Title and Context\n",
        "\n",
        "## Hotel Revenue Quality & Cancellation Intelligence\n",
        "### Turning Booking Data into Decision Support for Hotel Management\n",
        "\n",
        "**Dataset:** City Hotel bookings, 2015–2017  \n",
        "**Records analyzed:** 77,795 bookings (after cleaning)  \n",
        "**Primary focus:** Revenue quality, cancellation behavior, booking patterns, guest behavioral signals  \n",
        "**Target audience:** Hotel General Manager / Director of Revenue\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# 2. Business Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "## Why This Project Exists\n",
        "\n",
        "Hotel accounting departments typically report three core metrics: **ADR (Average Daily Rate)**, **Occupancy Rate**, and **RevPAR (Revenue Per Available Room)**. These metrics are well understood, widely tracked, and genuinely useful for benchmarking.\n",
        "\n",
        "But they share a critical blind spot.\n",
        "\n",
        "**They measure what was booked — not what was earned.**\n",
        "\n",
        "A hotel reporting 80% occupancy and €150k in revenue for a given month looks identical on a standard report whether 95% of those bookings completed or only 55% completed. The accounting system records the booking; it does not systematically track whether that booking translated into a real stay.\n",
        "\n",
        "This gap is not a reporting failure. It is a structural limitation of traditional hotel accounting. Revenue management systems handle some of this complexity, but in many city hotels — particularly those without dedicated revenue management functions — the gap between booked revenue and realized revenue remains invisible at the management level.\n",
        "\n",
        "**This project fills that gap.**\n",
        "\n",
        "By analyzing 77,795 city hotel bookings across three years, this project builds a revenue quality intelligence framework that answers four questions accounting does not:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Which bookings are actually reliable?** (Not all bookings are equal.)\n",
        "2. **Which segments and channels produce real revenue versus phantom bookings?**\n",
        "3. **What behavioral signals at the time of booking predict whether a guest will cancel?**\n",
        "4. **Where should management focus policy changes to improve revenue stability?**\n",
        "\n",
        "These are not academic questions. They have direct operational and financial consequences for any hotel management team.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "### The Scale of the Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "Before any analysis, one number frames the entire project:\n",
        "\n",
        "> Of €25,199,012 in total booked room revenue across the analysis period, only **€14,348,156** was realized from completed stays.\n",
        "\n",
        "That is a **realization rate of 56.9%.**\n",
        "\n",
        "The hotel is booking, processing, managing, and staffing for revenue that cancels at nearly the same rate as it completes. Understanding why — and what to do about it — is the core purpose of this project.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# 3. Project Objectives\n",
        "\n",
        "### Primary Objectives\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Measure revenue quality** — not just revenue volume — using realization rate as the primary KPI\n",
        "2. **Identify which market segments and distribution channels produce reliable revenue** versus high-cancellation exposure\n",
        "3. **Discover behavioral patterns** that predict cancellation at the time of booking\n",
        "4. **Quantify the financial impact** of cancellations by segment, channel, and geographic source\n",
        "5. **Provide actionable, evidence-based recommendations** for hotel management\n",
        "\n",
        "### Secondary Objectives\n",
        "\n",
        "6. **Analyze seasonal cancellation patterns** to enable time-sensitive policy calibration\n",
        "7. **Investigate geographic concentration** of cancellation risk\n",
        "8. **Distinguish between operationally different non-completion events** (true cancellations vs. No-Shows)\n",
        "9. **Demonstrate that BI analysis complements — rather than duplicates — traditional accounting functions**\n",
        "\n",
        "### What This Project Does NOT Attempt\n",
        "\n",
        "- Machine learning prediction models (not justified for this use case — rule-based risk flagging is more transparent and operationally trusted)\n",
        "- Dynamic pricing optimization (requires competitor pricing data not available here)\n",
        "- Final invoice reconciliation (accounting function — outside the scope of booking data analysis)"
      ],
