        "**Observation:** Cancellation rate increases consistently with lead time — from 10.4% at 0-2 days to 50.1% at 30+ days. The pattern is perfectly linear without exception across all four buckets. 71% of all bookings are in the highest-risk bucket.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Interpretation:** The behavioral logic is straightforward. A guest booking today for tonight is ready to travel — their commitment is near-certain. A guest booking 60 days in advance is making a speculative commitment. Plans change, better prices appear, circumstances shift. The further in advance a booking is made, the more opportunities exist for that commitment to evaporate. The OTA model — which encourages early booking with flexible cancellation policies — structurally maximizes bookings in the highest-risk lead time bucket.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Business implication:** Uniform cancellation policies that do not distinguish between a 2-day booking and a 90-day booking are treating fundamentally different risk profiles identically. Lead time is the simplest and most predictive variable for calibrating deposit and cancellation policy terms.\n"
