        "**Observation:** A guest making zero special requests cancels at 55.6%. One special request reduces this to 22.2% — a drop of more than half. The pattern continues declining to 3.8% for guests making five requests.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Interpretation:** Special requests are a proxy for guest investment in their stay. A guest who asked for a high floor, a quiet room, or an early check-in has mentally committed to the visit. They have pictured themselves at the hotel. This psychological investment creates a real-world friction against cancellation. A guest who made no special requests was likely booking speculatively — holding a slot while remaining open to alternatives. 47,121 bookings (60% of the dataset) fall in the zero-request category, and 55.6% of them cancel. This is the largest single risk pool in the hotel's portfolio.\n",
