    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# 7. Deep Business Insights\n",
        "## 7.1 Revenue Quality: The Gap Between Booked and Earned\n",
        "\n",
        "The fundamental analytical contribution of this project is distinguishing between two types of revenue that standard hotel reporting treats identically:\n",
        "\n",
        "**Booked Revenue:** The total value of all reservations at the contracted rate. This is what accounting records when a reservation is made.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Realized Revenue:** The total value of reservations that resulted in a completed stay. This is what the hotel actually earned.\n",
        "\n",
        "The relationship between them — the **realization rate** — varies enormously by segment:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Segment | Realization Rate | What It Means |\n",
        "|---|---|---|\n",
        "| Groups | 31.4% | 69 cents of every booked euro is never received |\n",
        "| Offline TA/TO | 57.1% | 43 cents of every booked euro is never received |\n",
        "| Online TA | 58.5% | 41 cents of every booked euro is never received |\n",
        "| Corporate | 75.5% | 24 cents of every booked euro is never received |\n",
        "| Direct | 78.1% | 22 cents of every booked euro is never received |\n",
        "\n",
        "A hotel reporting strong ADR and occupancy from a Groups-heavy booking mix may be significantly over-estimating its revenue position relative to what will actually complete.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 7.2 The Five Behavioral Predictors\n",
        "\n",
        "Five variables in the dataset independently predict cancellation behavior with consistent, measurable patterns. These signals are available at or near the time of booking and require no additional data collection.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Predictor 1: Total Special Requests\n",
        "- 0 requests → 55.6% cancellation\n",
        "- 1+ requests → ~22% cancellation\n",
        "- Signal type: Pre-arrival commitment indicator\n",
        "\n",
        "### Predictor 2: Previous Cancellations\n",
        "- 0 previous cancellations → 38.5% cancellation\n",
        "- 1 previous cancellation → 96.6% cancellation\n",
        "- Signal type: Historical behavioral indicator (strongest single predictor)\n",
        "\n",
        "### Predictor 3: Booking Changes\n",
        "- 0 modifications → 45.9% cancellation\n",
        "- 1+ modifications → 14.0% cancellation\n",
        "- Signal type: Post-booking engagement indicator\n",
        "\n",
        "### Predictor 4: Lead Time\n",
        "- 0-2 days → 10.4% cancellation\n",
        "- 30+ days → 50.1% cancellation\n",
        "- Signal type: Temporal commitment indicator\n",
        "\n",
        "### Predictor 5: Repeated Guest Status\n",
        "- First-time guest → 42.6% cancellation\n",
        "- Returning guest → 25.7% cancellation\n",
        "- Signal type: Loyalty and familiarity indicator\n",
        "\n",
        "These five predictors were tested individually. Their combined effect has not been formally modeled in this project — that represents a natural extension into a composite risk scoring tool.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 7.3 The Non Refund Anomaly\n",
        "\n",
        "One of the most important analytical discoveries in this project concerns the `deposit_type` column.\n",
        "\n",
        "Initial hypothesis: Non Refund bookings should cancel least — guests who have already paid have a financial incentive to complete their stay.\n",
        "\n",
        "Data finding: Non Refund bookings cancel at 99.8% — the highest rate of any deposit category.\n",
        "\n",
        "Investigation finding: 97% of Non Refund cancellations belong to Groups and Offline TA/TO market segments with an average lead time of 217 days.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Explanation:** These are not individual guest non-refundable bookings. They are wholesale allotment contracts — a tour operator pre-loads 50 rooms 7 months in advance under non-refundable wholesale terms, then releases unused rooms closer to the date. Each released room records as a \"canceled\" Non Refund booking in the PMS. This is standard hotel revenue management practice, not individual guest behavior.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Analytical implication:** The `deposit_type` column in this dataset cannot be used as a proxy for individual guest financial commitment. The field is being used for wholesale contract classification, not consumer payment terms.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Revenue implication:** The €3,160,849 in Non Refund canceled revenue cannot be confidently classified as \"secured.\" Whether these allotment contracts required upfront payment depends on individual contract terms that are not available in the booking data. Accounting records would be required to confirm actual cash collection.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 7.4 The Corporate Segment Tradeoff\n",
        "\n",
        "Corporate bookings present a nuanced picture that resists simple classification as either \"good\" or \"bad.\"\n",
        "\n",
        "**The reliability case for Corporate:**\n",
        "- 21.6% cancellation rate — below the hotel average\n",
        "- 75.5% realization rate — above the hotel average\n",
        "- Consistent, predictable booking behavior\n",
        "\n",
        "**The value case against prioritizing Corporate growth:**\n",
        "- Lowest average ADR of any commercial segment: €84.21\n",
        "- Shortest average stay: 1.88 nights\n",
        "- Realized revenue per booking attempt: €124 — second lowest commercial figure\n",
        "\n",
        "Both facts are verified in the data. The explanation: Corporate bookings are governed by annual negotiated contracts with discounted rates and short-stay patterns. The hotel trades revenue per booking for reliability.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Strategic conclusion:** Corporate's role is as a base-load segment — it stabilizes occupancy and provides reliable revenue floors, particularly during shoulder periods. It should not be confused with a high-revenue growth target. Recommending Corporate expansion without acknowledging the €124 realized revenue per booking attempt would be misleading.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 7.5 Portugal — A Segment Problem Wearing a Geographic Mask\n",
        "\n",
        "Portugal representing 60.7% of all cancellations on 38.4% of bookings initially appears to be a country-level problem requiring a country-specific intervention.\n",
        "\n",
        "Investigation revealed it is not.\n",
        "\n",
        "Portuguese bookings are concentrated in Groups (36.5%) and Offline TA/TO (31.2%) — together 67.7% of Portuguese bookings sit in the hotel's two worst-performing segments. International bookings are 68.3% Online TA with only 6.0% in Groups.\n",
        "\n",
        "Portugal's cancellation problem is structurally identical to the hotel's Groups and Offline TA/TO problem. It is concentrated geographically because the domestic Portuguese market channels its bookings disproportionately through wholesale and group arrangements.\n",
        "\n",
        "France (19.6% cancellation) and Germany (17.7% cancellation) are the hotel's most reliable large source markets — canceling below even the Direct booking rate — because their booking mix is less concentrated in the high-cancellation segments.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# 8. Important Analytical Reasoning\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.1 Why \"Groups\" Means Two Different Things\n",
        "\n",
        "The word \"Groups\" appears in two columns in this dataset and means fundamentally different things in each:\n",
        "\n",
        "**`market_segment = 'Groups'`** (13,809 bookings, 69.5% cancellation)  \n",
        "This describes how the booking was sourced — through a group sales channel. The customers themselves are overwhelmingly Transient and Transient-Party types with no binding contracts. The channel is used by tour operators, event organizers, and wholesale agents who pre-load room blocks and release what they cannot sell.\n",
        "\n",
        "**`customer_type = 'Group'`** (283 bookings, 10.2% cancellation)  \n",
        "This describes the contractual nature of the booking — a formally structured group agreement with defined terms and commitments. These are found across many market segments, not just the Groups market segment channel.\n",
        "\n",
        "**The crosstab proof:**\n",
        "\n",
        "| | customer_type: Group | customer_type: Transient | customer_type: Transient-Party |\n",
        "|---|---|---|---|\n",
        "| market_segment: Groups | 4 | 6,787 | 6,317 |\n",
        "\n",
        "Only 4 bookings are simultaneously in both. The two columns are measuring almost entirely different populations despite sharing the same word.\n",
        "\n",
        "An analyst who reads \"Groups cancel at 10.2%\" from the customer_type column and concludes group bookings are reliable — without checking which column produced that number — would reach a completely wrong conclusion about one of the hotel's highest-risk booking sources.\n",
        "\n",
        "This type of data semantics problem is common in PMS-generated datasets and requires domain knowledge to detect.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 8.2 Why Accounting Reports Cannot Show What This Project Shows\n",
        "\n",
        "Hotel accounting systems are designed to track financial obligations — revenue committed, costs incurred, profit generated. They are optimized for financial accuracy, not behavioral prediction.\n",
        "\n",
        "The `is_canceled` flag in the PMS exists to mark a booking as inactive for billing purposes. It is not designed as an analytical variable. When an analyst extracts it and uses it to calculate cancellation rates, they are repurposing operational data for analytical use — a valid and valuable practice, but one that requires careful interpretation.\n",
        "\n",
        "For example: the fact that `is_canceled = True` includes both cancellations and No-Shows is not a data quality problem. It reflects how the system was designed. The accounting implication of a cancellation and a No-Show may be identical (no revenue collected). The operational implication is entirely different (one gives advance notice, one does not). An analyst must understand the operational system to interpret the data correctly.\n",
        "\n",
        "This project demonstrates that distinction throughout — separating cancellations from No-Shows wherever the difference operationally matters.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "06TRRIAYgiTl"
      }
    },
