        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.4 ADR as a Revenue Metric — Limitations\n",
        "\n",
        "ADR is a useful summary metric but carries three limitations that this project accounts for:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **ADR does not capture non-room revenue.** F&B, spa, parking, and ancillary charges are excluded. A Bed & Breakfast booking generates more total revenue than ADR alone shows.\n",
        "\n",
        "2. **ADR is the contracted rate, not the final invoiced amount.** Discounts applied at check-in, loyalty redemptions, and billing adjustments are not reflected in the booking ADR.\n",
        "\n",
        "3. **A high ADR segment with a low realization rate is not necessarily more valuable than a lower ADR segment with a high realization rate.** The Corporate segment illustrates this: ADR of €84.21 but realization rate of 75.5% produces more reliable revenue per booking attempt than an OTA segment with €119 ADR and 58.5% realization.\n",
        "\n",
        "All revenue conclusions in this project use realized revenue — not ADR — as the primary revenue quality metric.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "# 10. Key Findings Summary\n",
        "\n",
        "## Executive Summary\n",
        "\n",
        "**The hotel has a revenue quality problem, not just a revenue volume problem.**\n",
        "\n",
        "Of €25.2 million booked, only €14.3 million was realized — a realization rate of 56.9%. The confirmed minimum revenue loss from No Deposit cancellations is €7.7 million annually. This gap is not random. It is structurally concentrated in specific segments, channels, lead time windows, and behavioral profiles — all of which are identifiable from data the hotel already collects.\n",
